#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:5
msgid "Builtin Tokens"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:9
msgid ""
"In the :mod:`pygments.token` module, there is a special object called "
"`Token` that is used to create token types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:12
msgid ""
"You can create a new token type by accessing an attribute of `Token` whose "
"name starts with an uppercase letter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:15
msgid ""
">>> from pygments.token import Token\n"
">>> Token.String\n"
"Token.String\n"
">>> Token.String is Token.String\n"
"True"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:23
msgid ""
"Note that tokens are singletons so you can use the ``is`` operator for "
"comparing token types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:26
msgid "You can also use the ``in`` operator to perform set tests:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:28
msgid ""
">>> from pygments.token import Comment\n"
">>> Comment.Single in Comment\n"
"True\n"
">>> Comment in Comment.Multi\n"
"False"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:36
msgid ""
"This can be useful in :doc:`filters <filters>` and if you write lexers on "
"your own without using the base lexers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:39
msgid ""
"You can also split a token type into a hierarchy, and get the parent of it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:41
msgid ""
">>> String.split()\n"
"[Token, Token.Literal, Token.Literal.String]\n"
">>> String.parent\n"
"Token.Literal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:48
msgid ""
"In principle, you can create an unlimited number of token types but nobody "
"can guarantee that a style would define style rules for a token type. "
"Because of that, Pygments proposes some global token types defined in the "
"`pygments.token.STANDARD_TYPES` dict."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:53
msgid "For some tokens aliases are already defined:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/tokens.rst:55
msgid ""
">>> from pygments.token import String\n"
">>> String\n"
"Token.Literal.String"
msgstr ""

